{"chunk_id": "d8cd2d32-ffdc-44b5-9e76-aabf37da0cb9", "source_database": "ICMR", "document_title": "ICMR_NIN_Dietary_Guidelines_Real.pdf", "publication_version": "Latest", "chunk_sequence_number": 111, "content_type": "Medical Guideline", "language": "English", "text": "milk may be started from 4 weeks of age. /c63Infants fed animal milk should receive supplements of iron and vitamin C. /c63About 120-180 ml of milk should be fed with one teaspoon of sugar per feed, 6-8 times over the day. /c63While reconstituting the infant formula, the instructions given on the label should be strictly followed. /c63The feeds should be prepared and given using a sterile cup, spoon, bottles and nipples taking utmost care. /c63Overfeeding should be avoided in artificially-fed infants to prevent obesity. /c63Low-cost home-made complementary foods should be preferred. WHAT SHOULD BE DONE IF BREAST-MILK IS NOT ADEQUATE? 32 POINTS TO PONDER COMPLEMENTARY FOODS Rice ... 35 g Green gram dhal ... 10 g Leafy vegetables ... 2 t. sp Fat ... 2 t. sp Cumin (jeera) Method :Clean rice", "embedding": [-0.013623207807540894, -0.03542206436395645, -0.017600759863853455, 0.047726865857839584, -0.03482924401760101, 0.06037599965929985, -0.08642565459012985, 0.07545839250087738, -0.10670982301235199, -0.04491329938173294, 0.056965604424476624, -0.08186378329992294, -0.10131669789552689, -0.03880716487765312, 0.047700073570013046, -0.030486837029457092, 0.10144373029470444, 0.022333800792694092, -0.02445370890200138, -0.09978672116994858, 0.0014027412980794907, -0.04981406778097153, 0.06707959622144699, 0.017150521278381348, 0.019101737067103386, -0.06011384353041649, 0.06413514912128448, -0.05593150854110718, 0.031909357756376266, 0.023968471214175224, -0.044407058507204056, -0.052282724529504776, 0.032387398183345795, -0.021011609584093094, -0.09432312846183777, 0.05001624673604965, 0.05251660943031311, -0.0931183248758316, -0.005941818468272686, -0.017509667202830315, 0.017748050391674042, -0.018796563